Zero values for input 2¶

The strong visual correlation of Input 2 and 3 should be investigated:

  • Input 2 values are 0 for some small periods due to some breakdown in the corresponding equipment. Due to correlation, Input 3 has also very low values

or

  • The equipment/sensor that generates Input 2 and 3 perform normally, however as the value for any of them is reduced under a certain threshold, the sensor just produces zero

Here we need to learn the reason for this situation.

Lag between Input 2 and 3¶

Another Key point is that, although Input 2 and 3 are moving paralelly, is there a lag between them? For this purpose I'm using cross correlation function

Reset Period¶

Returning back to the period in which all the inputs are 0 along with our target variable. Since we are dealing with time series data, the zero values cannot be omitted due to the continuity in our timestamps.

Since the gap is quite high, it's meaningful to impute that data according to timestamp characteristics. I need to visualize hourly, daily, weekly movements in the data

Here we see that

  • Input 2 and 3 fluctuates heavily throughout a month.
  • All of our inputs and targets follow a certain movement throughout the week, but in average
  • Only input_2 displays a meaningful behaviour for hourly values, yet it's in average.

The Reset Period - 1¶

Normally, I would really love to imputate the values that are 0, because it is really a sign of one or two things:

  • A temporary maintenance: data could be refetched from archive
  • Any type of incenvenience: imputate the data

However in our case, we assume that everything's fine, all readings are accurate etc. In that case these 0 values in the reset period is part of our dataset and should be included in our final prediction model. On the other hand, prior to our predictive model, we need to investigate characteristics of our dataset. That's why I'll make this inspection with a interpolated version of the set.

Milliseconds Shift¶

This is one of the interesting things about our data, the time difference between our measurements are exactly 0 days 00:59:59.995 milliseconds.

  • Is it a glitch in the sensor?
  • There are readings in every 5 milliseconds, but only these ones are sampled
  • Readings are sent 5 ms earlier before the exact hour, so the network delay will not overflow to the next hour.

Stationarity¶

In [101]:
def check_mean_std(data):
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(7, figsize=(18, 18))
    fig.suptitle('Moving Average and STDs')
    for i in range(len(numeric_cols)):
        timeseries = data[numeric_cols[i]]
        rolmean = timeseries.rolling(window=20).mean()
        rolstd = timeseries.rolling(window=20).std()

        orig = axs[i].plot(timeseries, color='red', label='Original')
        mean = axs[i].plot(rolmean, color='black', label='Rolling Mean')
        std = axs[i].plot(rolstd, color='green', label='Rolling Std')

check_mean_std(df_interpolated)

As we visually check the constant means and constant STDs,

  • Target: Fails to have both due to fluctuation in the period before reset
  • Input_1: Has constant mean and STD
  • Input_2: Does not have constant mean, yet has constant STD
  • Input_3: Does not have constant mean, yet has constant STD
  • Input_4: Has constant mean and STD
  • Input_5: Has constant mean and STD
  • Input_6: Has constant mean and STD

Resolving Nonstationairty¶

Detrending & Differencing¶

In [103]:
non_stationary_cols = ['target', 'input_2', 'input_3']

fig, axs = plt.subplots(3,3, figsize=(18,18))
fig.suptitle('Moving Average and STDs')
for i in range(len(non_stationary_cols)):
    col=non_stationary_cols[i]
    
    #detrending
    ts = df_interpolated[col]
    window_size = 20
    moving_avg = ts.rolling(window=window_size).mean()

    #
    ts_moving_avg_diff = ts - moving_avg
    ts_moving_avg_diff.dropna(inplace=True)
    
    ts_diff = ts_moving_avg_diff - ts_moving_avg_diff.shift()
    
    axs[i,0].plot(ts, color='red',label='Original')
    axs[i,1].plot(ts_moving_avg_diff, label='Detrended')
    axs[i,2].plot(ts_diff, label='Differenced')
    
    funcs.check_stationarity(ts_moving_avg_diff, col)

In this section we need to investigate the dependency of our inputs among each other and with the target in terms of, causality and cointegration.

Cointegration¶

Here I'll check for the Johansen cointegration test results, if the resulting eigenvalue modulos are smaller than 1. Normally this is necessity for vector autocorrelation models, yet I need to make sure if I can use all of the inputs.

Causality¶

I have already performed a cross correlation test for inputs 2 and 3, I want to see a better picture of all the variables.

In [105]:
input_cols = ['input_1','input_2','input_3','input_4','input_5','input_6']
for i in range(len(input_cols)):
    for j in range(i+1, len(input_cols)):
        ccres = ccf(df_non_reset[input_cols[i]], df_non_reset[input_cols[j]], adjusted=True)
        if ccres.max()>0.3:
            rs=ccres
            offset = np.floor(len(rs)/2)-np.argmax(rs)
            f,ax=plt.subplots(figsize=(14,3))
            ax.plot(rs)
            ax.axvline(np.ceil(len(rs)/2),color='k',linestyle='--',label='Center')
            ax.axvline(np.argmax(rs),color='r',linestyle='--',label='Peak synchrony')
            ax.set(title='Offset = {} frames\n {} leads <> {} leads'.format(offset, input_cols[i], input_cols[j]), xlabel='Offset',ylabel='Pearson r')

            plt.legend()

According to result of our lagged cross correlations, we have figured out that, the synch between high correlation inputs are really low. So it's safe to say the causality is minimal in this set

import keras
def model_builder(hp):
    '''
    Args:
    hp - Keras tuner object
    '''
    # Initialize the Sequential API and start stacking the layers
    
    model = Sequential()
    hp_initial_units = hp.Int('units_initial_layer', min_value=128, max_value=512, step=128)
    model.add(LSTM(units = hp_initial_units,  input_shape=(x_train_lstm.shape[1], x_train_lstm.shape[2]), return_sequences=True))
    
    hp_initial_dropout_threshold = hp.Float('initial_dropout_threshold', min_value=0, max_value=0.2, step=0.2)
    model.add(Dropout(hp_initial_dropout_threshold))
    
    for i in range(hp.Int('layers', 0, 1)):
        hp_units = hp.Int('units_'+str(i), min_value=128, max_value=512, step=128)
        model.add(LSTM(units=hp_units ,input_shape=(x_train_lstm.shape[1], x_train_lstm.shape[2]), return_sequences=True))
    
    hp_dropout_threshold = hp.Float('dropout_threshold', min_value=0.0, max_value=0.2, step=0.2)
    model.add(Dropout(hp_dropout_threshold))
    
    model.add(Dense(1))
    model.add(Activation('linear'))    

    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse')
    return model

# Instantiate the tuner
tuner = kt.Hyperband(model_builder, # the hypermodel
                     objective='val_loss', # objective to optimize
max_epochs=25,
factor=3, # factor which you have seen above

project_name='khyperband')

Cross Validation¶

Rather than using a bigger model, a more lightweight model could be used to make things faster, with the expense of a slight performance loss.

no_epochs=200
batch_size = 256
verbosity=0
num_folds  = 10



kfold = KFold(n_splits=num_folds, shuffle=True)
# K-fold Cross Validation model evaluation
fold_no = 1
loss_per_fold=[]
for train, test in kfold.split(x_train_sc, y_train):
    model3 = Sequential()
    model3.add(LSTM(49,  input_shape=(x_train_lstm.shape[1], x_train_lstm.shape[2])))
    model3.add(Dropout(0.1))
    model3.add(Dense(1))
    model3.add(Activation("linear"))
    model3.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse')


    # Generate a print
    print('------------------------------------------------------------------------')
    print(f'Training for fold {fold_no} ...')

    # Fit data to model
#     history = model3.fit(x_train_sc[train], y_train.values[train],
#               batch_size=batch_size,
#               epochs=no_epochs,
#               verbose=verbosity)
    history = model3.fit(x_train_sc[train], y_train.values[train], epochs=no_epochs, verbose=0)
    scores = model3.evaluate(x_train_sc[test], y_train.values[test], verbose=1, batch_size=batch_size, return_dict=True)
    print(f'Score for fold {fold_no}: {model3.metrics_names[0]} of {scores["loss"]}')
    loss_per_fold.append(scores['loss'])
    
    fold_no += 1
